ng the evolution of Zolf’s writing from an autobiographical poetics, in which Zolf as subject/speaker is locatable, toward a poetics that moves beyond the self to address political and ethical relations among subjects of geopolitics and settler colonialism. In her afterword, Zolf focuses on her most recent work, in which poems are composed almost entirely from archival sources and enact a kind of collective assemblage of enunciation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAmerican poetry. 4aLiterary Criticism: Canadian Literature. 4aPoetry. 4aSocial Science: Gender Studies. 4aSocial Science: Women’s studies. 7aPOETRY / Canadian.2bisacsh  aCanadian literature.  aethics.  afeminist poetics.  aphilosophy.  apoetics.  apoetry and ethics.  apoetry and politics.  apoetry.  aqueer poetry.  awomen's writing.1 aBesner, Neil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHenderson, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMilne, Heather, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311127268908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2019z978311127498040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978177112413340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781771124133423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781771124133/original  a978-3-11-127268-9  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  a978-3-11-127498-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles